# User-Facing vs Internal Naming

When a feature is rebranded or repositioned, there are two layers of naming:

## User-facing strings (safe to change)

UI labels, placeholder text, notification copy, AI system prompts, onboarding descriptions, App Store text. These can be updated freely to reflect new positioning.

## Internal identifiers (do NOT rename)

Database tables, column names, settings keys, analytics event names, component filenames, hook names, query keys, and route paths. These have persistence and backward compatibility implications — renaming them breaks older app versions, stored user data, or analytics pipelines.

## When rebranding a feature

1. Update all user-facing strings to the new name
2. Keep all internal identifiers unchanged
3. Update the feature's PRD to document the mapping between internal and external names (see `docs/prds/` for examples)
4. Update `docs/feature-positioning.md` with the new user-facing name
5. See `.cursor/rules/backward-compatibility.mdc` for the full backward compatibility policy

